# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: satellite-constellation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Beamforming can be used for radio or sound waves.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] It has found numerous applications in radar, sonar, seismology, wireless communications, radio astronomy, acoustics and biomedicine.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Adaptive beamforming is used to detect and estimate the signal of interest at the output of a sensor array by means of optimal (e.g., least-squares) spatial filtering and interference rejection.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] To change the directionality of the array when transmitting, a beamformer controls the phase and relative amplitude of the signal at each transmitter, in order to create a pattern of constructive and destructive interference in the wavefront.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] When receiving, information from different sensors is combined in a way where the expected pattern of radiation is preferentially observed.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] The beamforming technique involves sending the pulse from each projector at slightly different times (the projector closest to the ship last), so that every pulse hits the ship at exactly the same time, producing the effect of a single strong pulse from a single powerful projector.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] The same technique can be carried out in air using loudspeakers, or in radar/radio using antennas.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Receive beamforming can also be used with microphones or radar antennas.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] With narrowband systems the time delay is equivalent to a "phase shift", so in this case the array of antennas, each one shifted a slightly different amount, is called a phased array.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] A narrow band system, typical of radars, is one where the bandwidth is only a small fraction of the center frequency.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] With wideband systems this approximation no longer holds, which is typical in sonars.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] In the receive beamformer the signal from each antenna may be amplified by a different "weight." Different weighting patterns (e.g., Dolph–Chebyshev) can be used to achieve the desired sensitivity patterns.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] A main lobe is produced together with nulls and sidelobes.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] As well as controlling the main lobe width (beamwidth) and the sidelobe levels, the position of a null can be controlled.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] This is useful to ignore noise or jammers in one particular direction, while listening for events in other directions.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] A similar result can be obtained on transmission.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] For the full mathematics on directing beams using amplitude and phase shifts, see the mathematical section in phased array.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Conventional beamformers, such as the Butler matrix, use a fixed set of weightings and time-delays (or phasings) to combine the signals from the sensors in the array, primarily using only information about the location of the sensors in space and the wave directions of interest.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] In contrast, adaptive beamforming techniques (e.g., MUSIC, SAMV) generally combine this information with properties of the signals actually received by the array, typically to improve rejection of unwanted signals from other directions.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] This process may be carried out in either the time or the frequency domain.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] As the name indicates, an adaptive beamformer is able to automatically adapt its response to different situations.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Some criterion has to be set up to allow the adaptation to proceed such as minimizing the total noise output.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Because of the variation of noise with frequency, in wide band systems it may be desirable to carry out the process in the frequency domain.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Beamforming can be computationally intensive.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Sonar phased array has a data rate low enough that it can be processed in real time in software, which is flexible enough to transmit or receive in several directions at once.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] In contrast, radar phased array has a data rate so high that it usually requires dedicated hardware processing, which is hard-wired to transmit or receive in only one direction at a time.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] However, newer field programmable gate arrays are fast enough to handle radar data in real time, and can be quickly re-programmed like software, blurring the hardware/software distinction.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Sonar beamforming utilizes a similar technique to electromagnetic beamforming, but varies considerably in implementation details.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Sonar applications vary from 1 Hz to as high as 2 MHz, and array elements may be few and large, or number in the hundreds yet very small.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] This will shift sonar beamforming design efforts significantly between demands of such system components as the "front end" (transducers, pre-amplifiers and digitizers) and the actual beamformer computational hardware downstream.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] High frequency, focused beam, multi-element imaging-search sonars and acoustic cameras often implement fifth-order spatial processing that places strains equivalent to Aegis radar demands on the processors.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Many sonar systems, such as on torpedoes, are made up of arrays of up to 100 elements that must accomplish beam steering over a 100 degree field of view and work in both active and passive modes.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Sonar arrays are used both actively and passively in 1-, 2-, and 3-dimensional arrays.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Sonar differs from radar in that in some applications such as wide-area-search all directions often need to be listened to, and in some applications broadcast to, simultaneously.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] In a narrowband sonar receiver, the phases for each beam can be manipulated entirely by signal processing software, as compared to present radar systems that use hardware to 'listen' in a single direction at a time.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Sonar also uses beamforming to compensate for the significant problem of the slower propagation speed of sound as compared to that of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] In side-look-sonars, the speed of the towing system or vehicle carrying the sonar is moving at sufficient speed to move the sonar out of the field of the returning sound "ping".
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] In addition to focusing algorithms intended to improve reception, many side scan sonars also employ beam steering to look forward and backward to "catch" incoming pulses that would have been missed by a single sidelooking beam.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] The delay-and-sum beamforming technique uses multiple microphones to localize sound sources.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] One disadvantage of this technique is that adjustments of the position or of the number of microphones changes the performance of the beamformer nonlinearly.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Additionally, due to the number of combinations possible, it is computationally hard to find the best configuration.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] One of the techniques to solve this problem is the use of genetic algorithms.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Such algorithm searches for the microphone array configuration that provides the highest signal-to-noise ratio for each steered orientation.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Experiments showed that such algorithm could find the best configuration of a constrained search space comprising ~33 million solutions in a matter of seconds instead of days.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Beamforming techniques used in cellular phone standards have advanced through the generations to make use of more complex systems to achieve higher density cells, with higher throughput.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] An increasing number of consumer 802.11ac Wi-Fi devices with MIMO capability can support beamforming to boost data communication rates.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] To receive (but not transmit), there is a distinction between analog and digital beamforming.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] For example, if there are 100 sensor elements, the "digital beamforming" approach entails that each of the 100 signals passes through an analog-to-digital converter to create 100 digital data streams.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Then these data streams are added up digitally, with appropriate scale-factors or phase-shifts, to get the composite signals.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] By contrast, the "analog beamforming" approach entails taking the 100 analog signals, scaling or phase-shifting them using analog methods, summing them, and then usually digitizing the *single* output data stream.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Digital beamforming has the advantage that the digital data streams (100 in this example) can be manipulated and combined in many possible ways in parallel, to get many different output signals in parallel.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] The signals from every direction can be measured simultaneously, and the signals can be integrated for a longer time when studying far-off objects and simultaneously integrated for a shorter time to study fast-moving close objects, and so on.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] This cannot be done as effectively for analog beamforming, not only because each parallel signal combination requires its own circuitry, but more fundamentally because digital data can be copied perfectly but analog data cannot.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] (There is only so much analog power available, and amplification adds noise.) Therefore, if the received analog signal is split up and sent into a large number of different signal combination circuits, it can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio of each.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] In MIMO communication systems with large number of antennas, so called massive MIMO systems, the beamforming algorithms executed at the digital baseband can get very complex.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] In addition, if all beamforming is done at baseband, each antenna needs its own RF feed.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] At high frequencies and with large number of antenna elements, this can be very costly, and increase loss and complexity in the system.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] To remedy these issues, hybrid beamforming has been suggested where some of the beamforming is done using analog components and not digital.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] There are many possible different functions that can be performed using analog components instead of at the digital baseband.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Beamforming, whether done digitally, or by means of analog architecture, has recently been applied in Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC), also known as Joint Communication and Sensing (JCAS), technology.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] For instance, a beamformer was suggested, in imperfect channel state information situations to perform communication tasks, while at the same time performing target detection to sense targets in the scene.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Beamforming can be used to try to extract sound sources in a room, such as multiple speakers in the cocktail party problem.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] This requires the locations of the speakers to be known in advance, for example by using the time of arrival from the sources to mics in the array, and inferring the locations from the distances.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Compared to carrier-wave telecommunications, natural audio contains a variety of frequencies.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] It is advantageous to separate frequency bands prior to beamforming because different frequencies have different optimal beamform filters (and hence can be treated as separate problems, in parallel, and then recombined afterward).
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Properly isolating these bands involves specialized non-standard filter banks.
[src:satellite-constellation/beamforming] Instead, filters can be designed in which only local frequencies are detected by each channel (while retaining the recombination property to be able to reconstruct the original signal), and these are typically non-orthogonal unlike the FFT basis.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A **communications satellite** is an artificial satellite that relays and amplifies radio telecommunication signals via a transponder; it creates a communication channel between a source transmitter and a receiver at different locations on Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Communications satellites are used for television, telephone, radio, internet, and military applications.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] However, most form satellite constellations in low Earth orbit, where ground antennas must track the satellites and switch between them frequently.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The radio waves used for telecommunications links travel by line of sight and so are obstructed by the curve of the Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The purpose of communications satellites is to relay the signal around the curve of the Earth allowing communication between widely separated geographical points.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Communications satellites operate across a wide range of radio and microwave frequencies.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] To avoid signal interference, international organizations have regulations for which frequency ranges or "bands" certain organizations are allowed to use.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This allocation of bands minimizes the risk of signal interference.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Clarke published an article titled "Extraterrestrial Relays" in the British magazine *Wireless World*.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The article described the fundamentals behind the deployment of artificial satellites in geostationary orbits to relay radio signals.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Clarke is often quoted as being the inventor of the concept of the communications satellite, and the term 'Clarke Belt' is employed as a description of the orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The first artificial Earth satellite was Sputnik 1, which was put into orbit by the Soviet Union on 4 October 1957.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] It was developed by Mikhail Tikhonravov and Sergey Korolev, building on work by Konstantin Tsiolkovsky.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Sputnik 1 was equipped with an on-board radio transmitter that worked on two frequencies of 20.005 and 40.002 MHz, or 7 and 15 meters wavelength.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The satellite was not placed in orbit to send data from one point on Earth to another, but the radio transmitter was meant to study the properties of radio wave distribution throughout the ionosphere.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The launch of Sputnik 1 was a major step in the exploration of space and rocket development, and marks the beginning of the Space Age.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] There are two major classes of communications satellites, *passive* and *active*.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Passive satellites only reflect the signal coming from the source, toward the direction of the receiver.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] With passive satellites, the reflected signal is not amplified at the satellite, and only a small amount of the transmitted energy actually reaches the receiver.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Since the satellite is so far above Earth, the radio signal is attenuated due to free-space path loss, so the signal received on Earth is very weak.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Active satellites, on the other hand, amplify the received signal before retransmitting it to the receiver on the ground.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Passive satellites were the first communications satellites, but are little used now.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Work that was begun in the field of electrical intelligence gathering at the United States Naval Research Laboratory in 1951 led to a project named Communication Moon Relay.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] After achieving the first transoceanic communication between Washington, D.C., and Hawaii on 23 January 1956, this system was publicly inaugurated and put into formal production in January 1960.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The first satellite purpose-built to actively relay communications was Project SCORE, led by Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA) and launched on 18 December 1958, which used a tape recorder to carry a stored voice message, as well as to receive, store, and retransmit messages.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] It was used to send a Christmas greeting to the world from U.S.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The satellite also executed several realtime transmissions before the non-rechargeable batteries failed on 30 December 1958 after eight hours of actual operation.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The direct successor to SCORE was another ARPA-led project called Courier.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Courier 1B was launched on 4 October 1960 to explore whether it would be possible to establish a global military communications network by using "delayed repeater" satellites, which receive and store information until commanded to rebroadcast them.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] After 17 days, a command system failure ended communications from the satellite.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] NASA's satellite applications program launched the first artificial satellite used for passive relay communications in Echo 1 on 12 August 1960.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Echo 1 was an aluminized balloon satellite acting as a passive reflector of microwave signals.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Communication signals were bounced off the satellite from one point on Earth to another.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This experiment sought to establish the feasibility of worldwide broadcasts of telephone, radio, and television signals.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Telstar was the first active, direct relay communications commercial satellite and marked the first transatlantic transmission of television signals.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Another passive relay experiment primarily intended for military communications purposes was Project West Ford, which was led by Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] After an initial failure in 1961, a launch on 9 May 1963 dispersed 350 million copper needle dipoles to create a passive reflecting belt.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Even though only about half of the dipoles properly separated from each other, the project was able to successfully experiment and communicate using frequencies in the SHF X band spectrum.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] An immediate antecedent of the geostationary satellites was the Hughes Aircraft Company's Syncom 2, launched on 26 July 1963.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Syncom 2 was the first communications satellite in a geosynchronous orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] It revolved around the Earth once per day at constant speed, but because it still had north–south motion, special equipment was needed to track it.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Its successor, Syncom 3, launched on 19 July 1964, was the first geostationary communications satellite.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Syncom 3 obtained a geosynchronous orbit, without a north–south motion, making it appear from the ground as a stationary object in the sky.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A direct extension of the passive experiments of Project West Ford was the Lincoln Experimental Satellite program, also conducted by the Lincoln Laboratory on behalf of the United States Department of Defense.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The LES-1 active communications satellite was launched on 11 February 1965 to explore the feasibility of active solid-state X band long-range military communications.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A total of nine satellites were launched between 1965 and 1976 as part of this series.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In the United States, 1962 saw the creation of the Communications Satellite Corporation (COMSAT) private corporation, which was subject to instruction by the US Government on matters of national policy.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Over the next two years, international negotiations led to the Intelsat Agreements, which in turn led to the launch of Intelsat 1, also known as Early Bird, on 6 April 1965, and which was the first commercial communications satellite to be placed in geosynchronous orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Subsequent Intelsat launches in the 1960s provided multi-destination service and video, audio, and data service to ships at sea (Intelsat 2 in 1966–67), and the completion of a fully global network with Intelsat 3 in 1969–70.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] When Intelsat was launched, the United States was the only launch source outside of the Soviet Union, who did not participate in the Intelsat agreements.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The Soviet Union launched its first communications satellite on 23 April 1965 as part of the Molniya program.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This program was also unique at the time for its use of what then became known as the Molniya orbit, which describes a highly elliptical orbit, with two high apogees daily over the northern hemisphere.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This orbit provides a long dwell time over Russian territory as well as over Canada at higher latitudes than geostationary orbits over the equator.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In the 2020s, the popularity of low Earth orbit satellite internet constellations providing relatively low-cost internet services led to reducing demand for new geostationary orbit communications satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Communications satellites usually have one of three primary types of orbit, while other orbital classifications are used to further specify orbital details.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] MEO and LEO are non-geostationary orbit (NGSO).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] As satellites in MEO and LEO orbit the Earth faster, they do not remain visible in the sky to a fixed point on Earth continually like a geostationary satellite, but appear to a ground observer to cross the sky and "set" when they go behind the Earth beyond the visible horizon.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Therefore, to provide continuous communications capability with these lower orbits requires a larger number of satellites, so that one of these satellites will always be visible in the sky for transmission of communication signals.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] However, due to their closer distance to the Earth, LEO or MEO satellites can communicate to ground with reduced latency and at lower power than would be required from a geosynchronous orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A low Earth orbit (LEO) typically is a circular orbit about 160 to 2,000 kilometres (99 to 1,243 mi) above the Earth's surface and, correspondingly, a period (time to revolve around the Earth) of about 90 minutes.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Because of their low altitude, these satellites are only visible from within a radius of roughly 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) from the sub-satellite point.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In addition, satellites in low Earth orbit change their position relative to the ground position quickly.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] So even for local applications, many satellites are needed if the mission requires uninterrupted connectivity.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Low-Earth-orbiting satellites are less expensive to launch into orbit than geostationary satellites and, due to proximity to the ground, do not require as high signal strength (signal strength falls off as the square of the distance from the source, so the effect is considerable).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Thus there is a trade off between the number of satellites and their cost.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In addition, there are important differences in the onboard and ground equipment needed to support the two types of missions.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A group of satellites working in concert is known as a satellite constellation.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Two such constellations, intended to provide satellite phone and low-speed data services, primarily to remote areas, are the Iridium and Globalstar systems.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The Iridium system has 66 satellites, which orbital inclination of 86.4° and inter-satellite links provide service availability over the entire surface of Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Starlink is a satellite internet constellation operated by SpaceX, that aims for global satellite Internet access coverage.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] It is also possible to offer discontinuous coverage using a low-Earth-orbit satellite capable of storing data received while passing over one part of Earth and transmitting it later while passing over another part.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This will be the case with the CASCADE system of Canada's CASSIOPE communications satellite.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Another system using this store and forward method is Orbcomm.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A medium Earth orbit is a satellite in orbit somewhere between 2,000 and 35,786 kilometres (1,243 and 22,236 mi) above the Earth's surface.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] MEO satellites are similar to LEO satellites in functionality.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] MEO satellites are visible for much longer periods of time than LEO satellites, usually between 2 and 8 hours.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] MEO satellites have a larger coverage area than LEO satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A MEO satellite's longer duration of visibility and wider footprint means fewer satellites are needed in a MEO network than a LEO network.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] One disadvantage is that a MEO satellite's distance gives it a longer time delay and weaker signal than a LEO satellite, although these limitations are not as severe as those of a GEO satellite.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Like LEOs, these satellites do not maintain a stationary distance from the Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This is in contrast to the geostationary orbit, where satellites are always 35,786 kilometres (22,236 mi) from Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Typically the orbit of a medium Earth orbit satellite is about 16,000 kilometres (10,000 mi) above Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In various patterns, these satellites make the trip around Earth in anywhere from 2 to 8 hours.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] To an observer on Earth, a satellite in a geostationary orbit appears motionless, in a fixed position in the sky.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This is because it revolves around the Earth at Earth's own angular velocity (one revolution per sidereal day, in an equatorial orbit).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A geostationary orbit is useful for communications because ground antennas can be aimed at the satellite without their having to track the satellite's motion.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In applications that require many ground antennas, such as DirecTV distribution, the savings in ground equipment can more than outweigh the cost and complexity of placing a satellite into orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] By 2000, Hughes Space and Communications (now Boeing Satellite Development Center) had built nearly 40 percent of the more than one hundred satellites in service worldwide.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Geostationary satellites must operate above the equator and therefore appear lower on the horizon as the receiver gets farther from the equator.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This will cause problems for extreme northerly latitudes, affecting connectivity and causing multipath interference (caused by signals reflecting off the ground and into the ground antenna).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Thus, for areas close to the North (and South) Pole, a geostationary satellite may appear below the horizon.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Therefore, Molniya orbit satellites have been launched, mainly in Russia, to alleviate this problem.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Molniya orbits can be an appealing alternative in such cases.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The Molniya orbit is highly inclined, guaranteeing good elevation over selected positions during the northern portion of the orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] (Elevation is the extent of the satellite's position above the horizon.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The Molniya orbit is designed so that the satellite spends the great majority of its time over the far northern latitudes, during which its ground footprint moves only slightly.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Its period is one half day, so that the satellite is available for operation over the targeted region for six to nine hours every second revolution.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In this way a constellation of three Molniya satellites (plus in-orbit spares) can provide uninterrupted coverage.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The first satellite of the Molniya series was launched on 23 April 1965 and was used for experimental transmission of TV signals from a Moscow uplink station to downlink stations located in Siberia and the Russian Far East, in Norilsk, Khabarovsk, Magadan and Vladivostok.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In November 1967 Soviet engineers created a unique system of national TV network of satellite television, called Orbita, that was based on Molniya satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In the United States, the National Polar-orbiting Operational Environmental Satellite System (NPOESS) was established in 1994 to consolidate the polar satellite operations of NASA (National Aeronautics and Space Administration) NOAA (National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] NPOESS manages a number of satellites for various purposes; for example, METSAT for meteorological satellite, EUMETSAT for the European branch of the program, and METOP for meteorological operations.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] These orbits are Sun synchronous, meaning that they cross the equator at the same local time each day.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] For example, the satellites in the NPOESS (civilian) orbit will cross the equator, going from south to north, at times 1:30 P.M., 5:30 P.M., and 9:30 P.M.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] There are plans and initiatives to bring dedicated communications satellite beyond geostationary orbits.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] NASA proposed LunaNet as a data network aiming to provide a "Lunar Internet" for cis-lunar spacecraft and Installations.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The Moonlight Initiative is an equivalent ESA project that is stated to be compatible and providing navigational services for the lunar surface.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Both programmes are satellite constellations of several satellites in various orbits around the Moon.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Other orbits are also planned to be used.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Positions in the Earth-Moon-Libration points are also proposed for communication satellites covering the Moon alike communication satellites in geosynchronous orbit cover the Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Also, dedicated communication satellites in orbits around Mars supporting different missions on surface and other orbits are considered, such as the Mars Telecommunications Orbiter.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The bandwidth available from a satellite depends upon the number of transponders provided by the satellite.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Each service (TV, Voice, Internet, radio) requires a different amount of bandwidth for transmission.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This is typically known as link budgeting and a network simulator can be used to arrive at the exact value.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Allocating frequencies to satellite services is a complicated process which requires international coordination and planning.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This is carried out under the auspices of the International Telecommunication Union (ITU).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Within these regions, frequency bands are allocated to various satellite services, although a given service may be allocated different frequency bands in different regions.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The first and historically most important application for communication satellites was in intercontinental long distance telephony.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The fixed Public Switched Telephone Network relays telephone calls from land line telephones to an Earth station, where they are then transmitted to a geostationary satellite.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Improvements in submarine communications cables through the use of fiber-optics caused some decline in the use of satellites for fixed telephony in the late 20th century.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Satellite communications are still used in many applications today.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Remote islands such as Ascension Island, Saint Helena, Diego Garcia, and Easter Island, where no submarine cables are in service, need satellite telephones.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] There are also regions of some continents and countries where landline telecommunications are rare to non existent, for example large regions of South America, Africa, Canada, China, Russia, and Australia.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Satellite communications also provide connection to the edges of Antarctica and Greenland.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Other land use for satellite phones are rigs at sea, a backup for hospitals, military, and recreation.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Ships at sea, as well as planes, often use satellite phones.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Satellite phone systems can be accomplished by a number of means.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] On a large scale, often there will be a local telephone system in an isolated area with a link to the telephone system in a main land area.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] There are also services that will patch a radio signal to a telephone system.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] In this example, almost any type of satellite can be used.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Satellite phones connect directly to a constellation of either geostationary or low-Earth-orbit satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Calls are then forwarded to a satellite teleport connected to the Public Switched Telephone Network .
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] As television became the main market, its demand for simultaneous delivery of relatively few signals of large bandwidth to many receivers being a more precise match for the capabilities of geosynchronous comsats.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Two satellite types are used for North American television and radio: Direct broadcast satellite (DBS), and Fixed Service Satellite (FSS).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The definitions of FSS and DBS satellites outside of North America, especially in Europe, are a bit more ambiguous.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Most satellites used for direct-to-home television in Europe have the same high power output as DBS-class satellites in North America, but use the same linear polarization as FSS-class satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Examples of these are the Astra, Eutelsat, and Hotbird spacecraft in orbit over the European continent.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Because of this, the terms FSS and DBS are more so used throughout the North American continent, and are uncommon in Europe.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Fixed Service Satellites use the C band, and the lower portions of the Ku band.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] FSS satellites are also used to distribute national cable channels to cable television headends.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Free-to-air satellite TV channels are also usually distributed on FSS satellites in the Ku band.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The Intelsat Americas 5, Galaxy 10R and AMC 3 satellites over North America provide a quite large amount of FTA channels on their Ku band transponders.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A direct broadcast satellite is a communications satellite that transmits to small DBS satellite dishes (usually 18 to 24 inches or 45 to 60 cm in diameter).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Direct broadcast satellites generally operate in the upper portion of the microwave Ku band.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] DBS technology is used for DTH-oriented (Direct-To-Home) satellite TV services, such as DirecTV, DISH Network and Orby TV in the United States, Bell Satellite TV and Shaw Direct in Canada, Freesat and Sky in the UK, Ireland, and New Zealand and DSTV in South Africa.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Operating at lower frequency and lower power than DBS, FSS satellites require a much larger dish for reception (3 to 8 feet (1 to 2.5 m) in diameter for Ku band, and 12 feet (3.6 m) or larger for C band).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] They use linear polarization for each of the transponders' RF input and output (as opposed to circular polarization used by DBS satellites), but this is a minor technical difference that users do not notice.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] FSS satellite technology was also originally used for DTH satellite TV from the late 1970s to the early 1990s in the United States in the form of TVRO (Television Receive Only) receivers and dishes.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] It was also used in its Ku band form for the now-defunct Primestar satellite TV service.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Some satellites have been launched that have transponders in the Ka band, such as DirecTV's SPACEWAY-1 satellite, and Anik F2.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] NASA and ISRO have also launched experimental satellites carrying Ka band beacons recently.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Some manufacturers have also introduced special antennas for mobile reception of DBS television.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Using Global Positioning System (GPS) technology as a reference, these antennas automatically re-aim to the satellite no matter where or how the vehicle (on which the antenna is mounted) is situated.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] These mobile satellite antennas are popular with some recreational vehicle owners.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Such mobile DBS antennas are also used by JetBlue Airways for DirecTV (supplied by LiveTV, a subsidiary of JetBlue), which passengers can view on-board on LCD screens mounted in the seats.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Satellite radio offers audio broadcast services in some countries, notably the United States.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Mobile services allow listeners to roam a continent, listening to the same audio programming anywhere.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] A satellite radio or subscription radio (SR) is a digital radio signal that is broadcast by a communications satellite, which covers a much wider geographical range than terrestrial radio signals.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Amateur radio operators have access to amateur satellites, which have been designed specifically to carry amateur radio traffic.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Most such satellites operate as spaceborne repeaters, and are generally accessed by amateurs equipped with UHF or VHF radio equipment and highly directional antennas such as Yagis or dish antennas.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Due to launch costs, most current amateur satellites are launched into fairly low Earth orbits, and are designed to deal with only a limited number of brief contacts at any given time.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Some satellites also provide data-forwarding services using the X.25 or similar protocols.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] After the 1990s, satellite communication technology has been used as a means to connect to the Internet via broadband data connections.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] This can be very useful for users who are located in remote areas, and cannot access a broadband connection, or require high availability of services.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Communications satellites are used for military communications applications, such as Global Command and Control Systems.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Examples of military systems that use communication satellites are the MILSTAR, the DSCS, and the FLTSATCOM of the United States, NATO satellites, United Kingdom satellites (for instance Skynet), and satellites of the former Soviet Union.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] India has launched its first Military Communication satellite GSAT-7, its transponders operate in UHF, F, C and Ku band bands.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Typically military satellites operate in the UHF, SHF (also known as X-band) or EHF (also known as Ka band) frequency bands.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] Near-ground *in situ* environmental monitoring equipment (such as tide gauges, weather stations, weather buoys, and radiosondes), may use satellites for one-way data transmission or two-way telemetry and telecontrol.
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] It may be based on a secondary payload of a weather satellite (as in the case of GOES and METEOSAT and others in the Argos system) or in dedicated satellites (such as SCD).
[src:satellite-constellation/communications-satellite] The data rate is typically much lower than in satellite Internet access.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Optical communications, in various forms, have been used for thousands of years.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The ancient Greeks used a coded alphabetic system of signalling with torches developed by Cleoxenus, Democleitus and Polybius.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In the modern era, semaphores and wireless solar telegraphs called heliographs were developed, using coded signals to communicate with their recipients.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In 1880, Alexander Graham Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter created the photophone, at Bell's newly established Volta Laboratory in Washington, DC.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Bell considered it his most important invention.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The device allowed for the transmission of sound on a beam of light.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] On June 3, 1880, Bell conducted the world's first wireless telephone transmission between two buildings, some 213 meters (699 feet) apart.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Its first practical use came in military communication systems many decades later, first for optical telegraphy.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] German colonial troops used heliograph telegraphy transmitters during the Herero Wars starting in 1904, in German South-West Africa (today's Namibia) as did British, French, US or Ottoman signals.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Optical telephone communications were tested at the end of the war, but not introduced at troop level.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In addition, special blinkgeräts were used for communication with airplanes, balloons, and tanks, with varying success.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] A major technological step was to replace the Morse code by modulating optical waves in speech transmission.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Carl Zeiss, Jena developed the **Lichtsprechgerät* 80/80* (literal translation: optical speaking device) that the German army used in their World War II anti-aircraft defense units, or in bunkers at the Atlantic Wall.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The invention of lasers in the 1960s revolutionized free-space optics.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Military organizations were particularly interested and boosted their development.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] However, laser-based free-space optics lost market momentum when the installation of optical fiber networks for civilian uses was at its peak.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Many simple and inexpensive consumer remote controls use low-speed communication using infrared (IR) light.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] This is known as consumer IR technologies.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Free-space point-to-point optical links can be implemented using infrared laser light, although low-data-rate communication over short distances is possible using LEDs.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Infrared Data Association (IrDA) technology is a very simple form of free-space optical communications.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] On the communications side the FSO technology is considered as a part of the optical wireless communications applications.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Free-space optics can be used for communications between spacecraft.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The reliability of FSO units has always been a problem for commercial telecommunications.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Consistently, studies find too many dropped packets and signal errors over small ranges (400 to 500 meters (1,300 to 1,600 ft)).
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] This is from both independent studies, such as in the Czech Republic, as well as internal studies, such as one conducted by MRV FSO staff.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Military based studies consistently produce longer estimates for reliability, projecting the maximum range for terrestrial links is of the order of 2 to 3 km (1.2 to 1.9 mi).
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] All studies agree the stability and quality of the link is highly dependent on atmospheric factors such as rain, fog, dust and heat.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Relays may be employed to extend the range for FSO communications.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] TMEX USA ran two eight-mile links between Laredo, Texas and Nuevo Laredo, Mexico from 1998 to 2002.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The links operated at 155 Mbit/s and reliably carried phone calls and internet service.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The main reason terrestrial communications have been limited to non-commercial telecommunications functions is fog.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Fog often prevents FSO laser links over 500 meters (1,600 ft) from achieving a year-round availability sufficient for commercial services.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Several entities are continually attempting to overcome these key disadvantages to FSO communications and field a system with a better quality of service.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] DARPA has sponsored over US$130 million in research toward this effort, with the ORCA and ORCLE programs.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Other non-government groups are fielding tests to evaluate different technologies that some claim have the ability to address key FSO adoption challenges.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] As of October 2014, none have fielded a working system that addresses the most common atmospheric events.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] FSO research from 1998 to 2006 in the private sector totaled $407.1 million, divided primarily among four start-up companies.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] One private company published a paper on November 20, 2014, claiming they had achieved commercial reliability (99.999% availability) in extreme fog.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] There is no indication this product is currently commercially available.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The massive advantages of laser communication in space have multiple space agencies racing to develop a stable space communication platform, with many significant demonstrations and achievements.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The first gigabit laser-based communication was achieved by the European Space Agency and called the European Data Relay System (EDRS) on November 28, 2014.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The system is operational and is being used on a daily basis.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In December 2023, the Australian National University (ANU) demonstrated its Quantum Optical Ground Station at its Mount Stromlo Observatory.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] QOGS uses adaptive optics and lasers as part of a telescope, to create a bi-directional communications system capable of supporting the NASA Artemis program to the Moon.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] A two-way distance record for communication was set by the Mercury laser altimeter instrument aboard the *MESSENGER* spacecraft.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] It was able to communicate across a distance of 24 million km (15 million mi), as the craft neared Earth on a fly-by in May 2005.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The previous record had been set with a one-way detection of laser light from Earth by the Galileo probe, of 6 million km (3.7 million mi) in 1992.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In January 2013, NASA used lasers to beam an image of the Mona Lisa to the Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter roughly 390,000 km (240,000 mi) away.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] To compensate for atmospheric interference, an error correction code algorithm similar to that used in CDs was implemented.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In the early morning hours of October 18, 2013, NASA's Lunar Laser Communication Demonstration (LLCD) transmitted data from lunar orbit to Earth at a rate of 622 megabits per second (Mbit/s).
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] LLCD was flown aboard the Lunar Atmosphere and Dust Environment Explorer (LADEE) spacecraft, whose primary science mission was to investigate the tenuous and exotic atmosphere that exists around the Moon.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Between April and July 2014 NASA's OPALS instrument successfully uploaded 175 megabytes in 3.5 seconds and downloaded 200–300 MB in 20 s.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Their system was also able to re-acquire tracking after the signal was lost due to cloud cover.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] On December 7, 2021 NASA launched the Laser Communications Relay Demonstration (LCRD), which aims to relay data between spacecraft in geosynchronous orbit and ground stations.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] LCRD is NASA's first two-way, end-to-end optical relay.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] LCRD uses two ground stations, Optical Ground Station (OGS)-1 and -2, at Table Mountain Observatory in California, and Haleakalā, Hawaii.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] One of LCRD's first operational users is the Integrated LCRD Low-Earth Orbit User Modem and Amplifier Terminal (ILLUMA-T), on the International Space Station.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The terminal will receive high-resolution science data from experiments and instruments on board the space station and then transfer this data to LCRD, which will then transmit it to a ground station.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] After the data arrives on Earth, it will be delivered to mission operation centers and mission scientists.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The ILLUMA-T payload was sent to the ISS in late 2023 on SpaceX CRS-29, and achieved first light on December 5, 2023.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] On April 28, 2023, NASA and its partners achieved 200 gigabit per second (Gbit/s) throughput on a space-to-ground optical link between a satellite in orbit and Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] This was achieved by the TeraByte InfraRed Delivery (TBIRD) system, mounted on NASA's Pathfinder Technology Demonstrator 3 (PTD-3) satellite.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Various satellite constellations that are intended to provide global broadband coverage, such as SpaceX Starlink, employ laser communication for inter-satellite links.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] This effectively creates a space-based optical mesh network between the satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In 2001, Twibright Labs released RONJA Metropolis, an open-source DIY 10 Mbit/s full-duplex LED FSO system that can span 1.4 km (0.87 mi).
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In 2004, a visible light communication consortium was formed in Japan.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] This was based on work from researchers that used a white LED-based space lighting system for indoor local area network (LAN) communications.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] These systems present advantages over traditional UHF RF-based systems from improved isolation between systems, the size and cost of receivers/transmitters, RF licensing laws and by combining space lighting and communication into the same system.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In January 2009, a task force for visible light communication was formed by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers working group for wireless personal area network standards known as IEEE 802.15.7.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Amateur radio operators have achieved significantly farther distances using incoherent sources of light from high-intensity LEDs.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] However, physical limitations of the equipment used limited bandwidths to about 4 kHz.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The high sensitivities required of the detector to cover such distances made the internal capacitance of the photodiode used a dominant factor in the high-impedance amplifier which followed it, thus naturally forming a low-pass filter with a cut-off frequency in the 4 kHz range.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Lasers can reach very high data rates which are comparable to fiber communications.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Projected data rates and future data rate claims vary.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] A low-cost white LED (GaN-phosphor) which could be used for space lighting can typically be modulated up to 20 MHz.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Data rates of over 100 Mbit/s can be achieved using efficient modulation schemes and Siemens claimed to have achieved over 500 Mbit/s in 2010.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Research published in 2009, used a similar system for traffic control of automated vehicles with LED traffic lights.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In September 2013, pureLiFi, the Edinburgh start-up working on Li-Fi, also demonstrated high speed point-to-point connectivity using any off-the-shelf LED light bulb.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] In previous work, high bandwidth specialist LEDs have been used to achieve the high data rates.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The new system, the Li-1st, maximizes the available optical bandwidth for any LED device, thereby reducing the cost and improving the performance of deploying indoor FSO systems.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] The light beam can be very narrow, which makes FSO hard to intercept, improving security.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Encryption can secure the data traversing the link.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] FSO provides vastly improved electromagnetic interference (EMI) behavior compared to using microwaves.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] These factors cause an attenuated receiver signal and lead to higher bit error ratio (BER).
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] To overcome these issues, vendors found some solutions, like multi-beam or multi-path architectures, which use more than one sender and more than one receiver.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Some state-of-the-art devices also have larger fade margin (extra power, reserved for rain, smog, fog).
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] To keep an eye-safe environment, good FSO systems have a limited laser power density and support laser classes 1 or 1M.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Atmospheric and fog attenuation, which are exponential in nature, limit practical range of FSO devices to several kilometers.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] However, free-space optics based on 1550 nm wavelength, have considerably lower optical loss than free-space optics using 830 nm wavelength, in dense fog conditions.
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] FSO using wavelength 1550 nm system are capable of transmitting several times higher power than systems with 850 nm and are safe to the human eye (1M class).
[src:satellite-constellation/free-space-optical-communication] Additionally, some free-space optics, such as EC SYSTEM, ensure higher connection reliability in bad weather conditions by constantly monitoring link quality to regulate laser diode transmission power with built-in automatic gain control.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] A **ground station**, **Earth station**, or **Earth terminal** is a terrestrial radio station designed for extraplanetary telecommunication with spacecraft (constituting part of the ground segment of the spacecraft system), or reception of radio waves from astronomical radio sources.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] Ground stations may be located either on the surface of the Earth, or in its atmosphere.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] Earth stations communicate with spacecraft by transmitting and receiving radio waves in the super high frequency (SHF) or extremely high frequency (EHF) bands (e.g. microwaves), or in the optical bands for laser communication (then called Optical Ground Station, OGS).
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] When a ground station successfully transmits radio waves to a spacecraft (or vice versa), it establishes a telecommunications link.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] A principal telecommunications device of the ground station is the parabolic antenna.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] Ground stations may have either a fixed or itinerant position.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] Article 1 § III of the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) Radio Regulations describes various types of stationary and mobile ground stations, and their interrelationships.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] Specialized **satellite Earth stations** or **satellite tracking stations** are used to telecommunicate with satellites — chiefly communications satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] Other ground stations communicate with crewed space stations or uncrewed space probes.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] A ground station that primarily receives telemetry data, or that follows space missions, or satellites not in geostationary orbit, is called a **ground tracking station**, or **space tracking station**, or simply a **tracking station**.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] When a spacecraft or satellite is within a ground station's line of sight, the station is said to have a *view* of the spacecraft (see *pass*).
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] A spacecraft can communicate with more than one ground station at a time.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] A pair of ground stations are said to have a spacecraft in *mutual view* when the stations share simultaneous, unobstructed, line-of-sight contact with the spacecraft.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] A *telecommunications port* — or, more commonly, *teleport* — is a satellite ground station that functions as a hub connecting a satellite or geocentric orbital network with a terrestrial telecommunications network, such as the Internet.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] Teleports may provide various broadcasting services among other telecommunications functions, such as uploading computer programs or issuing commands over an uplink to a satellite.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] In May 1984, the Dallas/Fort Worth Teleport became the first American teleport to commence operation.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] In Federal Standard 1037C, the United States General Services Administration defined an *Earth terminal complex* as the assemblage of equipment and facilities necessary to integrate an Earth terminal (ground station) into a telecommunications network.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] FS-1037C has since been subsumed by the ATIS Telecom Glossary, which is maintained by the Alliance for Telecommunications Industry Solutions (ATIS), an international, business-oriented, non-governmental organization.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] The Telecommunications Industry Association also acknowledges this definition.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] The ITU Radiocommunication Sector (ITU-R), a division of the International Telecommunication Union, codifies international standards agreed-upon through multinational discourse.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] From 1927 to 1932, the International Consultative Committee for Radio administered standards and regulations now governed by the ITU-R.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] In addition to the body of standards defined by the ITU-R, each major satellite operator provides technical requirements and standards that ground stations must meet in order to communicate with the operator's satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] For example, Intelsat publishes the Intelsat Earth Station Standards (IESS) which, among other things, classifies ground stations by the capabilities of their parabolic antennas, and pre-approves certain antenna models.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] Eutelsat publishes similar standards and requirements, such as the Eutelsat Earth Station Standards (EESS).
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] The Interagency Operations Advisory Group offers a Service Catalog describing standard services, Spacecraft Emergency Cross Support Standard, and Consultative Committee for Space Data Systems data standards.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] The Teleport (originally called a *Telecommunications Satellite Park*) innovation was conceived and developed by Joseph Milano in 1976 as part of a National Research Council study entitled, *Telecommunications for Metropolitan Areas: Near-Term Needs and Opportunities*.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] A network of ground stations is a group of stations located to support spacecraft communication, tracking, or both.
[src:satellite-constellation/ground-station] A network is established to provide dedicated support to a specific mission, function, program or organization.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] A **low Earth orbit** (**LEO**) is an orbit around Earth with a period of 128 minutes or less (making at least 11.25 orbits per day) and an eccentricity less than 0.25.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The term *LEO region* is used for the area of space below an altitude of 2,000 km (1,200 mi) (about one-third of Earth's radius).
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Objects in orbits that pass through this zone, even if they have an apogee further out or are sub-orbital, are carefully tracked since they present a collision risk to the many LEO satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The only human spaceflights to go beyond LEO are the lunar missions of the Apollo program from 1968 to 1972 and the Artemis II lunar flyby in 2026.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] All space stations as of 2026 have operated in geocentric orbits within LEO.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] A wide variety of sources define LEO in terms of altitude.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The altitude of an object in an elliptic orbit can vary significantly along the orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Even for circular orbits, the altitude above ground can vary by as much as 30 km (19 mi) (especially for polar orbits) due to the oblateness of Earth's spheroid figure and local topography.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] While definitions based on altitude are inherently ambiguous, most of them fall within the range specified by an orbit period of 128 minutes because, according to Kepler's third law, this corresponds to a semi-major axis of 8,413 km (5,228 mi).
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] For circular orbits, this in turn corresponds to an altitude of 2,042 km (1,269 mi) above the mean radius of Earth, which is consistent with some of the upper altitude limits in some LEO definitions.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The LEO region is defined by some sources as a region in space that LEO orbits occupy.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Some highly elliptical orbits may pass through the LEO region near their lowest altitude (or perigee) but are not in a LEO orbit because their highest altitude (or apogee) exceeds 2,000 km (1,243 mi).
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Sub-orbital objects can also reach the LEO region but are not in a LEO orbit because they re-enter the atmosphere.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The distinction between LEO orbits and the LEO region is especially important for analysis of possible collisions between objects which may not themselves be in LEO but could collide with satellites or debris in LEO orbits.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The mean orbital velocity needed to maintain a stable low Earth orbit is about 7.8 km/s (4.8 mi/s), which translates to 28,000 km/h (17,000 mph).
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] However, this depends on the exact altitude of the orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Calculated for a circular orbit of 200 km (120 mi) the orbital velocity is 7.79 km/s (4.84 mi/s), but for a higher 1,500 km (930 mi) orbit the velocity is reduced to 7.12 km/s (4.42 mi/s).
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The launch vehicle's delta-v needed to achieve low Earth orbit starts around 9.4 km/s (5.8 mi/s).
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The pull of gravity in LEO is only slightly less than on the Earth's surface.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] This is because the distance to LEO from the Earth's surface is much less than the Earth's radius.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] However, an object in orbit is in a permanent free fall around Earth, because in orbit the gravitational force and the centrifugal force balance each other out.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] As a result, spacecraft in orbit continue to stay in orbit, and people inside or outside such craft continuously experience weightlessness.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Objects in LEO orbit Earth between the denser part of the atmosphere and below the inner Van Allen radiation belt.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] They encounter atmospheric drag from gases in the thermosphere (approximately 80–600 km above the surface) or exosphere (approximately 600 km or 400 mi and higher), depending on orbit height.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Satellites in orbits involving altitudes below 300 km (190 mi) are subject to quick orbital decay due to atmospheric drag.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Equatorial low Earth orbits (**ELEO**) are a subset of LEO.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] These orbits, with low orbital inclination, allow rapid revisit times over low-latitude locations on Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Prograde equatorial LEOs also have lower delta-v launch requirements because they take advantage of the Earth's rotation.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Other useful LEO orbits, including polar orbits and Sun-synchronous orbits, have higher inclinations to the equator and provide coverage for higher latitudes on Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Some of the first generation of Starlink satellites used polar orbits which provide coverage everywhere on Earth.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Later Starlink constellations orbit at a lower inclination and provide more coverage for populated areas.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Higher orbits include medium Earth orbit (MEO), sometimes called intermediate circular orbit (ICO), and further above, geostationary orbit (GEO).
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Orbits higher than low orbit can lead to early failure of electronic components due to intense radiation and charge accumulation.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] In 2017, "very low Earth orbits" (**VLEO**) began to be seen in regulatory filings.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] These orbits, below about 450 km (280 mi), require the use of novel technologies for orbit raising because they operate in orbits that would ordinarily decay too soon to be economically useful.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] A low Earth orbit requires the lowest amount of energy for satellite placement.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] It provides high bandwidth and low communication latency.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Satellites and space stations in LEO are more accessible for crew and servicing.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Since it requires less energy to place a satellite into a LEO, and a satellite there needs less powerful amplifiers for successful transmission, LEO is used for many communication applications, such as the Iridium phone system.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Some communication satellites use much higher geostationary orbits and move at the same angular velocity as the Earth as to appear stationary above one location on the planet.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Unlike geosynchronous satellites, satellites in low orbit have a small field of view and can only observe and communicate with a fraction of the Earth at a given time.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] This means that a large network (or constellation) of satellites is required to provide continuous coverage.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Satellites at lower altitudes of orbit are in the atmosphere and suffer from rapid orbital decay, requiring either periodic re-boosting to maintain stable orbits, or the launching of replacements for those that re-enter the atmosphere.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The effects of adding such quantities of vaporized metals to Earth's stratosphere are potentially of concern but currently unknown.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The LEO environment is becoming congested with space debris because of the frequency of object launches.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] This has caused growing concern in recent years, since collisions at orbital velocities can be dangerous or deadly.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] Collisions can produce additional space debris, creating a domino effect known as the Kessler syndrome.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] NASA's Orbital Debris Program tracks over 25,000 objects larger than 10 cm diameter in LEO, while the estimated number between 1 and 10 cm is 500,000, and the number of particles bigger than 1 mm exceeds 100 million.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The particles travel at speeds up to 7.8 km/s (28,000 km/h; 17,500 mph), so even a small impact can severely damage a spacecraft.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The lifespan of space debris can vary wildly depending on their respective ballistic coefficient, and most importantly their initial orbit altitude.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] At lower orbit altitudes such as 400 km small spacecraft can decay within 5 years.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] However at altitudes above 500 km some spacecraft will take more than 25 years to deorbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The oldest piece of space debris that can be found in LEO is the Vanguard 1 satellite and its third-stage booster.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] The satellite was launched in 1958 and currently has a perigee of 651 km and an apogee of 4,226 km, placing part of its orbit within the higher region of Low Earth Orbit and extending into medium Earth orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/low-earth-orbit] It is currently expected to remain in orbit for 240 years.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] A **satellite constellation** is a group of artificial satellites working together as a system.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Unlike a single satellite, a constellation can provide permanent global or near-global coverage, such that at any time everywhere on Earth at least one satellite is visible.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Satellites are typically placed in sets of complementary orbital planes and connect to globally distributed ground stations.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] They may also use inter-satellite communication.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Satellites in medium Earth orbit (MEO) and low Earth orbit (LEO) are often deployed in satellite constellations, because the coverage area provided by a single satellite only covers a small area that moves as the satellite travels at the high angular velocity needed to maintain its orbit.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Many MEO or LEO satellites are needed to maintain continuous coverage over an area.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] This contrasts with geostationary satellites, where a single satellite, at a much higher altitude and moving at the same angular velocity as the rotation of the Earth's surface, provides permanent coverage over a large area.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] For some applications, in particular digital connectivity, the lower altitude of MEO and LEO satellite constellations provide advantages over a geostationary satellite, with lower path losses (reducing power requirements and costs) and latency.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] The propagation delay for a round-trip internet protocol transmission via a geostationary satellite can be over 600 ms, but as low as 125 ms for a MEO satellite or 30 ms for a LEO system.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Designing a satellite constellation (i.e., determining the orbital distribution of its constituents) is a complex problem that typically uses satellite-to-target coverage as the primary figure of merit.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Naturally, the resulting constellation depends on the mission requirements and objectives and can be characterized by its geometry.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] That is, either symmetric or asymmetric constellations.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Symmetric constellations are traditionally proposed for applications that require global coverage (e.g., telecommunications).
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Notable symmetric constellations proposed in the literature include Walker Delta and Star , and Rosette.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Asymmetric constellations are typically adopted when regional coverage (i.e., the distribution of targets is concentrated around specific locations rather than being globally uniform) is required.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Asymmetric constellations are proposed to address disaster monitoring, orbital debris remediation, and cislunar space domain awareness.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] The need for optimization in constellation design arises from the large number of degrees of freedom in the design space.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] For example, the payload characteristics, required temporal coverage resolution (e.g., continuous or discontinuous), targets' distribution, and candidate orbits.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] There are a large number of constellations that may satisfy a particular mission.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Usually constellations are designed so that the satellites have similar orbits, eccentricity and inclination so that any perturbations affect each satellite in approximately the same way.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] In this way, the geometry can be preserved without excessive station-keeping thereby reducing the fuel usage and hence increasing the life of the satellites.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Another consideration is that the phasing of each satellite in an orbital plane maintains sufficient separation to avoid collisions or interference at orbit plane intersections.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] A class of circular orbit geometries that has become popular is the Walker Delta Pattern constellation.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] This has an associated notation to describe it which was proposed by John Walker.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] For example, the Galileo navigation system is a Walker Delta 56°: 24/3/1 constellation.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] This means there are 24 satellites in 3 planes inclined at 56 degrees, spanning the 360 degrees around the equator.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] The "1" defines the phasing between the planes, and how they are spaced.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] The Walker Delta is also known as the Ballard rosette, after A.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Ballard's notation is (t,p,m) where m is a multiple of the fractional offset between planes.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Another popular constellation type is the near-polar Walker Star, which is used by Iridium.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Here, the satellites are in near-polar circular orbits across approximately 180 degrees, travelling north on one side of the Earth, and south on the other.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] The active satellites in the full Iridium constellation form a Walker Star of 86.4°: 66/6/2, i.e. the phasing repeats every two planes.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Walker uses similar notation for stars and deltas, which can be confusing.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] These sets of circular orbits at constant altitude are sometimes referred to as orbital shells.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] In spaceflight, an **orbital shell** is a set of artificial satellites in circular orbits at a certain fixed altitude.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] In the design of satellite constellations, an orbital shell usually refers to a collection of circular orbits with the same altitude and, oftentimes, orbital inclination, distributed evenly in celestial longitude (and mean anomaly).
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] For a sufficiently high inclination and altitude the orbital shell covers the entire orbited body.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] In other cases the coverage extends up to a certain maximum latitude.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] Several existing satellite constellations typically use a single orbital shell.
[src:satellite-constellation/satellite-constellation] New large megaconstellations have been proposed that consist of multiple orbital shells.
